{"id":"1610.02976","submitter":"Dibyendu Mandal","authors":"R K P Zia, Jeffrey B Weiss, Dibyendu Mandal and Baylor Fox-Kemper","title":"Manifest and Subtle Cyclic Behavior in Nonequilibrium Steady States","comments":"4 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":"Journal of Physics: Conference Series 750, 012003 (2016)","doi":"10.1088/1742-6596/750/1/012003","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech physics.ao-ph physics.bio-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Many interesting phenomena in nature are described by stochastic processes\nwith irreversible dynamics. To model these phenomena, we focus on a master\nequation or a Fokker-Planck equation with rates which violate detailed balance.\nWhen the system settles in a stationary state, it will be a nonequilibrium\nsteady state (NESS), with time independent probability distribution as well as\npersistent probability current loops. The observable consequences of the latter\nare explored. In particular, cyclic behavior of some form must be present: some\nare prominent and manifest, while others are more obscure and subtle. We\npresent a theoretical framework to analyze such properties, introducing the\nnotion of \"probability angular momentum\" and its distribution. Using several\nexamples, we illustrate the manifest and subtle categories and how best to\ndistinguish between them. These techniques can be applied to reveal the NESS\nnature of a wide range of systems in a large variety of areas. We illustrate\nwith one application: variability of ocean heat content in our climate system.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 10 Oct 2016 16:09:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-10-11"}
