{"id":"1610.03027","submitter":"David Ellis","authors":"David Ellis and Noam Lifshitz","title":"On the union of intersecting families","comments":"13 pages. Updated references, expositional changes and minor\n  corrections following the helpful comments of an anonymous referee","journal-ref":"Combinator. Probab. Comp. 28 (2019) 826-839","doi":"10.1017/S096354831900004X","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  A family of sets is said to be \\emph{intersecting} if any two sets in the\nfamily have nonempty intersection. In 1973, Erd\\H{o}s raised the problem of\ndetermining the maximum possible size of a union of $r$ different intersecting\nfamilies of $k$-element subsets of an $n$-element set, for each triple of\nintegers $(n,k,r)$. We make progress on this problem, proving that for any\nfixed integer $r \\geq 2$ and for any $k \\leq (\\tfrac{1}{2}-o(1))n$, if $X$ is\nan $n$-element set, and $\\mathcal{F} = \\mathcal{F}_1 \\cup \\mathcal{F}_2 \\cup\n\\ldots \\cup \\mathcal{F}_r$, where each $\\mathcal{F}_i$ is an intersecting\nfamily of $k$-element subsets of $X$, then $|\\mathcal{F}| \\leq {n \\choose k} -\n{n-r \\choose k}$, with equality only if $\\mathcal{F} = \\{S \\subset X:\\ |S|=k,\\\nS \\cap R \\neq \\emptyset\\}$ for some $R \\subset X$ with $|R|=r$. This is best\npossible up to the size of the $o(1)$ term, and improves a 1987 result of\nFrankl and F\\\"uredi, who obtained the same conclusion under the stronger\nhypothesis $k < (3-\\sqrt{5})n/2$, in the case $r=2$. Our proof utilises an\nisoperimetric, influence-based method recently developed by Keller and the\nauthors.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 10 Oct 2016 19:00:05 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 7 Feb 2017 09:59:05 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Mon, 20 Aug 2018 14:47:06 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Fri, 21 Dec 2018 10:33:34 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-10-09"}
