{"id":"1610.03231","submitter":"Gabriel Voitcu","authors":"Gabriel Voitcu, Marius Echim, Richard Marchand","title":"Comparative study of forward and backward test-kinetic simulation\n  approaches","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Computer Physics Communications 183, 2561-2569, 2012","doi":"10.1016/j.cpc.2012.07.005","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.plasm-ph physics.comp-ph physics.space-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper we perform a comparative study of the forward and backward\nLiouville mapping applied to the modeling of ring-shaped and non-gyrotropic\nvelocity distribution functions of particles injected in a sheared\nelectromagnetic field. The test-kinetic method is used to compute the velocity\ndistribution function in various areas of a proton cloud moving in the vicinity\nof a region with a sharp transition of the magnetic field and a non-uniform\nelectric field. In the forward approach the velocity distribution function is\ncomputed for a two-dimensional spatial bin, while in the backward approach the\ndistribution function is averaged over a spatial bin with the same size as for\nthe forward method and using a two-dimensional trapezoidal integration scheme.\nIt is shown that the two approaches lead to similar results for spatial bins\nwhere the velocity distribution function varies smoothly. On the other hand,\nwith bins covering regions of configuration space characterized by sharp\nspatial gradients of the velocity distribution function, the forward and\nbackward approaches will generally provide different results.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 11 Oct 2016 08:14:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-10-12"}
